properties.abstract: In three one-day stages, the ViaStockalper leads through sun-drenched valleys, pretty forests and rocky gorges in the Upper Valais. While the first stage climbs steeply from Brig to the Simplon pass, the two following stages descend steadily first to Simplon Dorf and then to Gondo.
properties.description:
The Simplon pass is closely associated with the industrious trading entrepreneur Kaspar Stockalper, who was born in Brig in 1609 and gave the route its name. As a politician, entrepreneur, benefactor and builder, he came into immeasurable wealth and continues to mark the Valais' natural environment to this day.

When the Thirty Years' War (1618-1648) caused traffic over the Graubünden passes and the Gotthard to grind to a halt, Stockalper established the route over the Simplon pass as a secure trade link across the alps, away from the turmoil of war. His European network of contacts and his excellent reputation protected him when he lost all his official functions and part of his fortune in 1678 and had to flee to Domodossola. The ViaStockalper follows the old mule track and offers insights into the Napoleonic and present-day road system.

A special feature of the hike is the barely populated, untamed area of natural terrain. For example, between the village of Simplon and the hamlet of Egga, the break-off of the Rossboden glacier in 1901 left a fifty-metre-high layer of debris and ice. Today, a marvellous larch forest grows there on large boulders, and this hike leads right through it.

The Taferna stream which foams down huge, forested steep slopes, is an experience in itself. On the Simplon pass, the highest point of the route, numerous small lakes are scattered across the barren, rugged high plateau between imposing peaks. 

Another special feature are the many traces that people have left on the route over the past centuries. The impressive Simplon hospice, commissioned by Napoleon, and the Old Spittel, completed by Kaspar Stockalper in 1666, are situated here on the pass. These are just two of the many centuries-old buildings that provided a resting place or retreat for travellers on the ViaStockalper. 

In the steep, rocky Gondo gorge, three traffic routes run closely next to and above each other. The stone slabs of Kaspar Stockalper's mule track, the bridges and wall supports of the Napoleon road and the modern national road cross each other in a dizzying manner. The military importance of the Simplon is made clear by the 350-metre tunnel which is part of the Gondo fortress.
